{{Short description|Vaccine against respiratory syncytial virus}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2024}}
{{cs1 config |name-list-style=vanc |display-authors=6}}

A '''respiratory syncytial virus vaccine''', or '''RSV vaccine''', is an annual [[vaccine]] that protects against [[respiratory syncytial virus]].<ref name="Arexvy EPAR" /> RSV affects an estimated 64 million people and causes 160,000 deaths worldwide each year.<ref name="niaid-rsv">{{cite web |date=22 July 2022 |title=Respiratory Syncytial Virus (RSV) – NIH: National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases |url=https://www.niaid.nih.gov/diseases-conditions/respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230424023336/https://www.niaid.nih.gov/diseases-conditions/respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv |archive-date=24 April 2023 |access-date=24 April 2023 |website=[[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]]}}</ref>

The RSV vaccines Arexvy ([[GSK plc|GSK]]),<ref name="Arexvy FDA label" /> Abrysvo ([[Pfizer]]),<ref name="Abrysvo FDA label" /> and Mresvia ([[Moderna]])<ref name="Mresvia FDA label" /> are approved for medical use in the United States.<ref name="FDA Arexvy" /><ref name="FDA Abrysvo">{{cite web | title=Abrysvo | website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) | date=1 June 2023 | url=https://www.fda.gov/vaccines-blood-biologics/abrysvo | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230602023847/https://www.fda.gov/vaccines-blood-biologics/abrysvo | url-status=dead | archive-date=2 June 2023 | access-date=2 June 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=31 May 2023 |title=US FDA approves Pfizer's RSV vaccine |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/healthcare-pharmaceuticals/us-fda-approves-pfizers-rsv-vaccine-2023-05-31/ |access-date=1 June 2023 |archive-date=22 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230822042904/https://www.reuters.com/business/healthcare-pharmaceuticals/us-fda-approves-pfizers-rsv-vaccine-2023-05-31/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Arexvy is approved for medical use in the United States,<ref name="Arexvy FDA label" /> in the European Union,<ref name="Arexvy EPAR" /><ref name="EU Arexvy Product Information" /> and in Canada for people aged 60 years of age and older.<ref>{{cite news | vauthors = La Grassa J |title=Health Canada approves 1st RSV vaccine for people 60 and older |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/health/rsv-health-canada-vaccine-1.6928175 |access-date=9 September 2023 |work=CBC News |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=4 August 2023 |archive-date=13 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230913131701/https://www.cbc.ca/news/health/rsv-health-canada-vaccine-1.6928175 |url-status=live }}</ref> Arexvy is approved in the US for people aged 50–59 years of age who are at increased risk.<ref name="FDA Arexvy" /><ref name="GSK PR 20240607">{{cite press release | title=US FDA approves expanded age indication for GSK's Arexvy, the first respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) vaccine for adults aged 50-59 at increased risk | website=GSK | date=7 June 2024 | url=https://us.gsk.com/en-us/media/press-releases/us-fda-approves-expanded-age-indication-for-gsk-s-arexvy-the-first-respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv-vaccine-for-adults-aged-50-59-at-increased-risk/ | access-date=11 June 2024 | archive-date=10 June 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240610182233/https://us.gsk.com/en-us/media/press-releases/us-fda-approves-expanded-age-indication-for-gsk-s-arexvy-the-first-respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv-vaccine-for-adults-aged-50-59-at-increased-risk/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fda.gov/media/179248/download |title=FDA approval letter |website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) |access-date=11 June 2024 |archive-date=11 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240611133143/https://www.fda.gov/media/179248/download |url-status=dead }}</ref> In June 2024, the US [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) updated its recommendation for the use of respiratory syncytial virus vaccine in people aged 60 years of age and older.<ref name="CDC 20240626" /> The CDC recommends that people who have not received the respiratory syncytial virus vaccine and are aged 75 years of age and older receive the respiratory syncytial virus vaccine; and that people who have not received the respiratory syncytial virus vaccine and are aged 60–74 years of age who are at increased risk of severe respiratory syncytial virus, meaning they have certain chronic medical conditions, such as lung or heart disease, or they live in nursing homes, receive the respiratory syncytial virus vaccine.<ref name="CDC 20240626">{{cite web | title=CDC Updates RSV Vaccination Recommendation for Adults | website=U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) | date=26 June 2024 | url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2024/s-0626-vaccination-adults.html | access-date=27 June 2024 | archive-date=7 July 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240707063033/https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2024/s-0626-vaccination-adults.html | url-status=live }} {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | vauthors = Mandavilli A | title=Federal Officials Revise Recommendations for R.S.V. Vaccine | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=26 June 2024 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2024/06/26/health/rsv-vaccine-cdc.html | access-date=27 June 2024 | archive-date=27 June 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240627011838/https://www.nytimes.com/2024/06/26/health/rsv-vaccine-cdc.html | url-status=live }}</ref>

A 2013 study led to the 2023 approval of RSV vaccines.<ref name="science2013" /><ref name="sa-202303" /> Work on RSV vaccines also supported the rapid development of [[COVID-19 vaccine]]s.<ref name="sa-202303" /><ref name="graham-202303">{{cite journal |vauthors=Graham BS |date=February 2023 |title=The Journey to RSV Vaccines — Heralding an Era of Structure-Based Design |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |volume=388 |issue=7 |pages=579–581 |doi=10.1056/NEJMp2216358 |pmid=36791157 |s2cid=256900516}}</ref> It is on the [[WHO Model List of Essential Medicines|World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines]].<ref name="WHO24th">{{cite book | vauthors = ((World Health Organization)) | title = The selection and use of essential medicines, 2025: WHO Model List of Essential Medicines, 24th list | year = 2025 | hdl = 10665/382243 | author-link = World Health Organization | publisher = World Health Organization | location = Geneva | hdl-access = free | doi = 10.2471/B09474 | doi-access = free | id = License: CC BY-NC-SA 3.0 IGO }}</ref>

== Medical uses ==
[[Respiratory syncytial virus]] vaccine is [[indicated]] for active immunization for the prevention of lower respiratory tract disease caused by respiratory syncytial virus in people 60 years of age and older.<ref name="Arexvy EPAR" /><ref name="Arexvy FDA label" /><ref name="Abrysvo FDA label" /><ref name="FDA PR 20240531" />

Abrysvo is indicated for active immunization for the prevention of lower respiratory tract disease caused by RSV in people 60 years of age and older, high-risk individuals aged 18 through 59 and pregnant individuals at 32 through 36 weeks gestational age to prevent severe disease in their infants from birth through six months of age.<ref name="Abrysvo FDA label" /><ref name="FDA Abrysvo" /><ref name="Abrysvo SmPC" /><ref name="Abrysvo EPAR" /><ref name="FDA PR 20230821">{{cite web |date=21 August 2023 |title=FDA Approves First Vaccine for Pregnant Individuals to Prevent RSV in Infants |url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-approves-first-vaccine-pregnant-individuals-prevent-rsv-infants |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230821215005/https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-approves-first-vaccine-pregnant-individuals-prevent-rsv-infants |archive-date=21 August 2023 |access-date=21 August 2023 |publisher=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA)}} {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref name="mmwr">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fleming-Dutra KE |date=6 October 2023 |title=Use of the Pfizer Respiratory Syncytial Virus Vaccine During Pregnancy for the Prevention of Respiratory Syncytial Virus–Associated Lower Respiratory Tract Disease in Infants: Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices — United States, 2023 |journal=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |volume=72 |issue=41 |pages=1115–1122 |doi=10.15585/mmwr.mm7241e1 |pmc=10578951 |pmid=37824423 |s2cid=263810212 |doi-access=free |title-link=doi}}</ref> Abrysvo is approved for use in pregnant women at 24 through 36 weeks and older adults in the European Union.<ref>{{cite news |date=24 August 2023 |title=EU approves Pfizer's RSV vaccine to protect infants and older adults |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/healthcare-pharmaceuticals/eu-approves-pfizers-rsv-vaccine-protect-infants-older-adults-2023-08-24/ |access-date=25 August 2023 |archive-date=25 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230825094132/https://www.reuters.com/business/healthcare-pharmaceuticals/eu-approves-pfizers-rsv-vaccine-protect-infants-older-adults-2023-08-24/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Abryvso product characteristics|url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/product-information/abrysvo-epar-product-information_en.pdf|publisher=European Medicines Agency|date=2023|access-date=2 December 2023|archive-date=2 December 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231202092142/https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/product-information/abrysvo-epar-product-information_en.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> and between 28 through 36 weeks and older adults in the United Kingdom.<ref name="Abrysvo SmPC" />

Infant-specific issues include the immature infant immune system and the presence of [[Passive immunity|maternal antibodies]], which make infantile [[immunization]] difficult.<ref name="Jha_201610">{{cite book |title=SARS, MERS and other Viral Lung Infections |vauthors=Jha A, Jarvis H, Fraser C, Openshaw PJ |date=2016 |publisher=European Respiratory Society |isbn=978-1-84984-070-5 |veditors=Hui DS, Rossi GA, Johnston SL |series=ERS Society Monographs |chapter=Respiratory Syncytial Virus |pmid=28742304 |id=Bookshelf ID: NBK442240 |chapter-url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK442240/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201228032145/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK442240/ |archive-date=28 December 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>

== History ==
=== Development ===
Attempts to develop an RSV vaccine began in the 1960s with an unsuccessful [[inactivated vaccine]] developed by exposing the RSV virus to [[formalin]] (formalin-inactivated RSV (FI-RSV)).<ref name="Acosta2015">{{cite journal |vauthors=Acosta PL, Caballero MT, Polack FP |title=Brief History and Characterization of Enhanced Respiratory Syncytial Virus Disease |journal=Clinical and Vaccine Immunology |date=December 2015 |volume=23 |issue=3 |pages=189–195 |doi=10.1128/CVI.00609-15 |pmid=26677198 |pmc=4783420}}</ref> This early vaccine induced [[vaccine-associated enhanced respiratory disease]] (VAERD), in which children who had not previously been exposed to RSV and were vaccinated would develop severe RSV disease if exposed to the virus itself, including [[fever]], [[wheezing]], and [[bronchopneumonia]].<ref name="Acosta2015" /> Some eighty percent of such children (vs. 5% of virus-exposed controls) were hospitalized, and two children died of lethal lung inflammation during the first natural RSV infection after vaccination of RSV-naive infants.<ref name="Acosta2015" /> This deadly vaccine failure slowed vaccine development for many years.<ref name="Acosta2015" />

A 1998 paper reported that research had advanced greatly over the previous ten years.<ref name="Dudas 1998">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dudas RA, Karron RA |title=Respiratory syncytial virus vaccines |journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews |date=July 1998 |volume=11 |issue=3 |pages=430–439 |pmid=9665976|pmc=88889 |doi=10.1128/CMR.11.3.430 }}</ref> A 2019 paper similarly claimed that research toward developing a vaccine had advanced greatly over the prior 10 years, with more than 30 candidates in some stage of development.<ref name="Mejias 2019">{{cite journal | vauthors = Mejias A, Rodriguez-Fernandez R, Peeples ME, Ramilo O |title=Respiratory Syncytial Virus Vaccines: Are We Making Progress? |journal=The Pediatric Infectious Disease Journal |date=October 2019 |volume=38 |issue=10 |pages=e266–e269 |doi=10.1097/INF.0000000000002404|pmid=31335571 |pmc=8404780 |doi-access=free | title-link = doi }}</ref> The same study predicted that a vaccine would be available within ten years.<ref name="Mejias 2019" /> Candidates included particle-based vaccines, [[attenuated vaccines]], [[mRNA vaccine]]s, [[protein subunit]] vaccines, and vector-based vaccines.<ref name="Mazur 2018">{{cite journal | vauthors = Mazur NI, Higgins D, Nunes MC, Melero JA, Langedijk AC, Horsley N, Buchholz UJ, Openshaw PJ, McLellan JS, Englund JA, Mejias A, Karron RA, Simões EA, Knezevic I, Ramilo O, Piedra PA, Chu HY, Falsey AR, Nair H, Kragten-Tabatabaie L, Greenough A, Baraldi E, Papadopoulos NG, Vekemans J, Polack FP, Powell M, Satav A, Walsh EE, Stein RT, Graham BS, Bont LJ |title=The respiratory syncytial virus vaccine landscape: lessons from the graveyard and promising candidates |journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases |date=October 2018 |volume=18 |issue=10 |pages=e295–e311 |doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(18)30292-5|pmid=29914800 |s2cid=49300571 |hdl=10044/1/61037 |hdl-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Powell K |date=December 2021|title=The race to make vaccines for a dangerous respiratory virus|journal=[[Nature (magazine)|Nature]]| volume=600| issue=7889| pages=379–380| doi=10.1038/d41586-021-03704-y| pmid=34893769|bibcode=2021Natur.600..379P|s2cid=245021172|doi-access=free | title-link = doi }}</ref>
	
A 2013 study detailed the crystal structure of the [[RSV fusion (F) protein]] and how its stability could be improved.<ref name="science2013">{{cite journal | vauthors = McLellan JS, Chen M, Joyce MG, Sastry M, Stewart-Jones GB, Yang Y, Zhang B, Chen L, Srivatsan S, Zheng A, Zhou T, Graepel KW, Kumar A, Moin S, Boyington JC, Chuang GY, Soto C, Baxa U, Bakker AQ, Spits H, Beaumont T, Zheng Z, Xia N, Ko SY, Todd JP, Rao S, Graham BS, Kwong PD |date=November 2013 |title=Structure-based design of a fusion glycoprotein vaccine for respiratory syncytial virus |journal=Science |volume=342 |issue=6158 |pages=592–598 |doi=10.1126/science.1243283 |pmc=4461862 |pmid=24179220 |bibcode=2013Sci...342..592M }}</ref> This provided the basis for finding the most effective F protein constructs, which are used in RSV vaccines.<ref name="sa-202303" /> To develop its vaccine, Pfizer engineered 400 different F protein constructs to identify the most immunogenic, and constructed a bivalent RSV prefusion F investigational vaccine.<ref name="science2023">{{cite journal | vauthors = Che Y, Gribenko AV, Song X, Handke LD, Efferen KS, Tompkins K, Kodali S, Nunez L, Prasad AK, Phelan LM, Ammirati M, Yu X, Lees JA, Chen W, Martinez L, Roopchand V, Han S, Qiu X, DeVincenzo JP, Jansen KU, Dormitzer PR, Swanson KA |date=April 2023 |title=Rational design of a highly immunogenic prefusion-stabilized F glycoprotein antigen for a respiratory syncytial virus vaccine |journal=Science Translational Medicine |volume=15 |issue=693 |article-number=eade6422 |doi=10.1126/scitranslmed.ade6422 |pmid=37023209 |s2cid=258007860 |doi-access=free | title-link = doi }}</ref>

In February 2023, results of a phase III study of around 25,000 participants age 60+ were published. One dose of the Arexvy vaccine provided 94% efficacy against severe RSV pneumonia and 72% efficacy against RSV acute respiratory infection.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Papi A, Ison MG, Langley JM, Lee DG, Leroux-Roels I, Martinon-Torres F, Schwarz TF, van Zyl-Smit RN, Campora L, Dezutter N, de Schrevel N, Fissette L, David MP, Van der Wielen M, Kostanyan L, Hulstrøm V |date=February 2023 |title=Respiratory Syncytial Virus Prefusion F Protein Vaccine in Older Adults |url=https://biblio.ugent.be/publication/01GWJBWW7HVDMHS20ZHQ89M4W8 |url-status=live |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |volume=388 |issue=7 |pages=595–608 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa2209604 |pmid=36791160 |s2cid=256900243 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230330015006/https://biblio.ugent.be/publication/01GWJBWW7HVDMHS20ZHQ89M4W8 |archive-date=30 March 2023 |access-date=22 August 2023|doi-access=free | title-link = doi |hdl=1959.4/unsworks_84474 |hdl-access=free }}</ref> An advisory panel to the FDA recommended approval of the vaccine in February 2023.<ref name="gsk-supply-202303">{{cite web |date=9 March 2023 |title=GSK expects US launch of RSV vaccine with no supply issues |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/healthcare-pharmaceuticals/gsk-set-us-launch-rsv-vaccine-with-no-supply-issues-2023-03-09/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230412172231/https://www.reuters.com/business/healthcare-pharmaceuticals/gsk-set-us-launch-rsv-vaccine-with-no-supply-issues-2023-03-09/ |archive-date=12 April 2023 |access-date=12 April 2023 |website=Reuters |vauthors=Fick M}}</ref><ref name="nbc-202302">{{cite news |date=28 February 2023 |title=Paving the way for the world's first RSV vaccine, FDA advisers recommend shot from Pfizer |work=NBC News |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/fda-advisers-recommend-first-rsv-vaccine-rcna72535 |url-status=live |access-date=28 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230228220644/https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/fda-advisers-recommend-first-rsv-vaccine-rcna72535 |archive-date=28 February 2023 |vauthors=Bendix A}}</ref>

In April 2023, the [[Committee for Medicinal Products for Human Use]] of the [[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) recommended to grant a marketing authorization for Arexvy for the prevention of RSV lower respiratory tract disease in people 60 years of age or older<ref name="Arexvy: Pending EC decision">{{cite web |date=26 April 2023 |title=Arexvy: Pending EC decision |url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/summaries-opinion/arexvy |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230427025107/https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/summaries-opinion/arexvy |archive-date=27 April 2023 |access-date=27 April 2023 |website=European Medicines Agency}} Text was copied from this source which is copyright European Medicines Agency. Reproduction is authorized provided the source is acknowledged.</ref><ref>{{cite press release |title=First vaccine to protect older adults from respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) infection |website=[[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) |date=26 April 2023 |url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/news/first-vaccine-protect-older-adults-respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv-infection |access-date=27 April 2023 |archive-date=27 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230427025104/https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/news/first-vaccine-protect-older-adults-respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv-infection |url-status=live}}</ref> after review under the EMA's accelerated assessment program.<ref name="Arexvy: Pending EC decision" />

In May 2023, Arexvy was approved for people aged 60 years of age and older, making it the first FDA-approved RSV vaccine.<ref name="FDA PR 20230504">{{cite press release |title=FDA Approves First Respiratory Syncytial Virus (RSV) Vaccine |publisher=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) |date=3 May 2023 |url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-approves-first-respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv-vaccine |access-date=3 May 2023 |archive-date=4 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230504230027/https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-approves-first-respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv-vaccine |url-status=dead}} {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref name="wapo050323">{{cite news |date=3 May 2023 |title=First vaccine targeting RSV wins FDA approval. More are coming. |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2023/05/03/rsv-vaccine-adults/ |url-status=live |access-date=3 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230822043342/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2023/05/03/rsv-vaccine-adults/ |archive-date=22 August 2023}}</ref>

In May 2023, the FDA's expert panel unanimously recommended Abrysvo for approval in pregnant women.<ref>{{cite news |date=18 May 2023 |title=FDA advisers support approval of RSV vaccine to protect infants |newspaper=[[NPR]] |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2023/05/18/1176863956/fda-advisers-support-approval-of-rsv-vaccine-to-protect-infants |access-date=24 May 2023 |vauthors=Hensley S, Stein R}}</ref> The panel was split on the safety of the vaccine in respect of preterm births.<ref>{{cite news |date=18 May 2023 |title=Pfizer's Maternal RSV Vaccine First to Win FDA Panel Support |work=Bloomberg.com |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-05-18/pfizer-s-maternal-rsv-vaccine-first-to-win-fda-advisers-support |url-status=live |access-date=1 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230522025604/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-05-18/pfizer-s-maternal-rsv-vaccine-first-to-win-fda-advisers-support |archive-date=22 May 2023}}</ref>

In June 2023, Arexvy was authorized for medical use in the European Union.<ref>{{cite press release |title=European Commission authorizes GSK's Arexvy, the first respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) vaccine for older adults |website=GSK |date=7 June 2023 |url=https://www.gsk.com/en-gb/media/press-releases/european-commission-authorises-gsk-s-arexvy-the-first-respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv-vaccine-for-older-adults/ |access-date=12 June 2023 |archive-date=13 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230613024855/https://www.gsk.com/en-gb/media/press-releases/european-commission-authorises-gsk-s-arexvy-the-first-respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv-vaccine-for-older-adults/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

The [[mRNA vaccine]] Mresvia was approved for medical use in the United States in May 2024.<ref name="FDA Mresvia" /><ref name="Moderna PR 20240531" /><ref name="FDA PR 20240531" />

In June 2024, the FDA approved Arexvy for use in people aged 50 to 59 years of age who are at an increased risk of RSV-caused lower respiratory tract disease.<ref name="GSK PR 20240607" /> The approval is based on data from a phase III study (NCT05590403),<ref name="NCT05590403">{{cite web | title=A Study on the Immune Response and Safety of a Vaccine Against Respiratory Syncytial Virus Given to Adults 50-59 Years of Age, Including Adults at Increased Risk of Respiratory Syncytial Virus Lower Respiratory Tract Disease, Compared to Older Adults 60 Years of Age and Above | website=ClinicalTrials.gov | url=https://www.clinicaltrials.gov/study/NCT05590403 | access-date=11 June 2024 | archive-date=4 March 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240304093754/https://www.clinicaltrials.gov/study/NCT05590403 | url-status=live }}</ref> which showed that immune responses were non-inferior in people aged 50–59 years of age at increased risk for RSV disease compared to people aged 60 years of age and older.<ref name=":0">{{Cite press release |date=25 October 2023 |title=New data for Arexvy, GSK's RSV vaccine, show potential to help protect adults aged 50 to 59 at increased risk for RSV disease |url=https://www.gsk.com/en-gb/media/press-releases/new-data-for-arexvy-show-potential-to-help-protect-adults-aged-50-to-59/ |access-date=11 June 2024 |website=GSK |archive-date=18 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240118094930/https://www.gsk.com/en-gb/media/press-releases/new-data-for-arexvy-show-potential-to-help-protect-adults-aged-50-to-59/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="NCT05590403" />

In October 2024, the FDA approved Abrysvo for the prevention of lower respiratory tract disease caused by respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) in individuals 18 through 59 years of age who are at increased risk for lower respiratory tract disease caused by RSV. Since 2023, Abrysvo has been approved for the prevention of lower respiratory tract disease caused by RSV in individuals 60 years of age and older and for use in pregnant individuals at 32 through 36 weeks gestational age for the prevention of lower respiratory tract disease and severe lower respiratory tract disease caused by RSV in infants from birth through six months of age.<ref name="FDA PR 20241025" /> Abrysvo is manufactured by Pfizer.<ref name="FDA PR 20241025">{{cite press release | title=FDA Roundup: October 25, 2024 | website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) | date=25 October 2024 | url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-roundup-october-25-2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241030214039/https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-roundup-october-25-2024 | url-status=dead | archive-date=30 October 2024 | access-date=27 October 2024}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>

Mresvia was authorized for medical use in the European Union in August 2024.<ref name="Mresvia EPAR" /><ref name="Mresvia PI" />

=== Clinical trials ===

{{As of|2022|10}}, [[Phases of clinical research#Phase III|phase III trials]] by multiple companies are ongoing to test RSV vaccines for people aged 60 years of age and older. These include vaccines by [[GSK plc|GSK]], [[Pfizer]], [[Johnson & Johnson]], [[Moderna]], and [[Bavarian Nordic]].<ref name="cnn-202210">{{cite news | vauthors = Goodman B |date=31 October 2022 |title=By the next RSV season, the US may have its first vaccine |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/10/31/health/rsv-vaccines-therapies/index.html |access-date=13 April 2023 |website=CNN |archive-date=14 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230414001216/https://www.cnn.com/2022/10/31/health/rsv-vaccines-therapies/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title = For decades, fear and failure in the hunt for an RSV vaccine. Now, success.|newspaper = [[The Washington Post]]|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2022/10/10/rsv-vaccine/|access-date = 11 October 2022|date = 10 October 2022|archive-date = 10 October 2022|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20221010213943/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2022/10/10/rsv-vaccine/|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = This UT Scientist Helped Spare Millions From COVID-19. Now He's Unmasking Other Killer Viruses |work = [[Texas Monthly]] |url = https://www.texasmonthly.com/news-politics/jason-mclellan-covid-vaccines-rsv/ |access-date = 13 October 2022 |date = 10 October 2022 |archive-date = 13 October 2022 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20221013143648/https://www.texasmonthly.com/news-politics/jason-mclellan-covid-vaccines-rsv/ |url-status = live }}</ref> {{As of|2023|04}}, other vaccines were in development, including vaccines for pregnant women to immunize their fetuses by passing maternal antibodies to them, and vaccines for children.<ref name="sa-202303">{{cite magazine | vauthors = Haelle T |title=RSV Vaccines Are Nearly Here after Decades of False Starts |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/rsv-vaccines-are-nearly-here-after-decades-of-false-starts/ | date=20 March 2023 |access-date=13 April 2023 |magazine=[[Scientific American]] |archive-date=12 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230412004511/https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/rsv-vaccines-are-nearly-here-after-decades-of-false-starts/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="cnn-202210" />

